properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Brief but intense snowfall with blowing snow expected Thursday morning. Total snowfall: 5 to 10 cm, with locally higher amounts possible. Wind gusts: up to 70 km/h Locations: Cape Breton and Eastern Nova Scotia. Time span: 3 A.M. to 9 A.M. Thursday morning. Remarks: A short period of heavy snow accompanied by strong northerly winds and blowing snow is forecast to move over eastern Nova Scotia early Thursday morning. Snowfall rates approaching 2 to 5 cm per hour and blowing snow will combine to give poor visibilities at times. Conditions will improve quickly as the snow tapers off later Thursday morning. At present, it is expected that the Sydney Metro and Cape Breton County region will avoid the heavier snow, strong winds, and blowing snow, but this could change if the track of the system responsible shifts further to the east. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-30T01:36:08-00:00

Area: Pictou County, Guysborough County, Antigonish County, Richmond County, Inverness County - south of Mabou, Inverness County - Mabou and north, Victoria County, Sydney Metro and Cape Breton County

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A frontal system moving across BC will spread snow to Highway 97 - Pine Pass beginning overnight. The snow is expected to be heaviest through the morning hours. Additionally, strong winds giving blowing snow may further reduce visibility. The heavy snow is expected to taper off to a few flurries in the afternoon. Warm air moving into the region could also result in flurries becoming mixed with rain showers in the afternoon. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard conditions will develop near White Pass today. A strong frontal system will move across southwestern Yukon today bringing snow and strong winds. Most of the South Klondike Highway will see periods of snow and blowing snow with the worst conditions expected to be by the border at White Pass. Visibilities in snow and blowing snow will be below 400 metres. Blizzard conditions will ease overnight. Local blowing snow will continue into Thursday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-30T00:03:53-00:00

properties.Title: Fog Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Near zero visibility in fog is expected or occurring over some areas. Dense fog persists tonight in areas of east-central Alberta and will gradually dissipate Wednesday morning. Areas of freezing drizzle are also possible along with the fog. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Fog advisories are issued when near zero visibilities in fog are expected or occurring. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility occasionally near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard conditions will return with strong winds redeveloping overnight. The blizzard will end early Thursday morning as the winds subside. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

Area: Dempster

properties.Title: Freezing Drizzle Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Areas of freezing drizzle are expected or occurring. Freezing drizzle will continue through to Wednesday morning. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing drizzle advisories are issued when drizzle falling in sub-zero temperatures is expected to freeze on contact, and over time create icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. The snow will become heavy tonight and continue through Wednesday. Total snowfall accumulations up to 35 cm are expected by Wednesday evening. At the same time, strong southerly winds associated with the storm in combination with the heavy snow will produce blowing snow and reduced visibilities. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-29T18:39:47-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-01-29T02:40:47-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0378703141.2020
Area: Haines Road - Haines Junction to Pleasant Camp
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Very strong wind gusts that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A deep low pressure system will track across the Gulf of Alaska tonight. A sharp cold front extending well to the south of the low will produce very strong southeasterly winds. Winds are expected to reach up to 120 km/h late this evening over Haida Gwaii and coastal communities stretching from Prince Rupert to Port Hardy. Once the cold front passes, winds will shift quickly to gusty southwesterlies overnight for Haida Gwaii and early Wednesday morning for Port Hardy. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-29T12:08:26-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-01-28T20:09:26-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0491850570.2020
Area: Haida Gwaii, North Vancouver Island, Central Coast - coastal sections, North Coast - coastal sections

properties.Title: Fog Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Near zero visibility in fog is expected or occurring. Extensive fog is developing again this evening. Widespread areas of near-zero visibility can be expected through the night. The fog will persist into Wednesday morning and improve in the afternoon. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
